I am new to *flutter* and I am trying to internationalize the content. I want to follow the &quot;flutter&quot; approach proposed in the flutter [tutorial][1].

My question concerns the **performance** of such implementation considering that it seems to me that every time a localized string has to be rendered first the corresponding Locale of its context is retrieved (with ```Localizations.of&lt;MyLocalizations&gt;(context, MyLocalizations)```), and then the localized value is obtained.

# Solution

After some thinking I found a solution myself. I have slightly modified the implementation as follows to avoid &quot;magic strings&quot; and force myself to explicitly translate any new string to all languages:

* A class `MyLocalizations` which encapsulates the handling of localized values, containing the current locale of the app. This class is designed to be used as a top level containers for localized strings getters, which are directly used to retrieve the underlying strings corresponding to the current locale the context. Under the hood this class is implemented as a **singleton**.

* A private class `_MyLocalizationsDelegate` which is the actual object handling the loading of locales by flutter. Its `load(Locale)` method simply calls a method from `MyLocalizations` which updates the singleton.

```dart
class MyLocalizations {
  /// Singleton.
  static final MyLocalizations _singleton = MyLocalizations._();

  /// A [LocalizationsDelegate] that uses [MyLocalizations.load] to create an instance of this class.
  static const LocalizationsDelegate&lt;MyLocalizations&gt; delegate = _MyLocalizationsDelegate();

  /// Locale name as defined by [Intl.canonicalizedLocale] (initialized to its [Intl.defaultLocale]).
  String _localeName = Intl.defaultLocale;

  /// Singleton constructor
  MyLocalizations._();

  /// Updates the locale definition of the singleton
  static Future&lt;MyLocalizations&gt; updateLocale(Locale locale) {
    // Get name
    final String name = locale.countryCode.isEmpty ? locale.languageCode : locale.toString();

    // Format name used by intl library
    final String localeName = Intl.canonicalizedLocale(name);

    // Update underlying locale name
    _singleton._localeName = localeName;

    return initializeMessages(localeName).then((_) =&gt; _singleton);
  }

  /// Short-hand facade method to get localized strings
  static String _message(String str, String name) =&gt; Intl.message(str, name: name, locale: _singleton._localeName);

  /// Log In button.
  static String get logIn =&gt; _message(&quot;Log In&quot;, &quot;logIn&quot;);

  /// Screen not found message.
  static String get screenNotFound =&gt; _message(&quot;Screen not found&quot;, &quot;screenNotFound&quot;);
}

class _MyLocalizationsDelegate extends LocalizationsDelegate&lt;MyLocalizations&gt; {
  /// Default explicit constructor
  const _MyLocalizationsDelegate();

  @override
  bool isSupported(Locale locale) =&gt; LanguageCodes.isSupported(locale.languageCode);

  @override
  Future&lt;MyLocalizations&gt; load(Locale locale) =&gt; MyLocalizations.updateLocale(locale);

  @override
  bool shouldReload(_MyLocalizationsDelegate old) =&gt; false;
}
```


  [1]: https://flutter.dev/docs/development/accessibility-and-localization/internationalization#an-alternative-class-for-the-apps-localized-resources

